</div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>I have a stove-top popper that I bought about 20 years ago.  It&#8217;s got a crank that moves a paddle around the bottom of the pot, so the kernels stay moving (and you don&#8217;t have to shake it, like the saucepans).  It works great, and I swear it&#8217;s actually faster than microwave popcorn.  Not to mention cheaper and tastier.  My 11-year-old son loves it (but he still likes MW popcorn now and again).</p>
<cite>&#8212; Will</cite>
</div>
</li>
<li id="comment-59227">
<div class="comment-meta">
<span class="comment-number">8. </span>
<span class="updated" title="2008-05-06T14:49:58+00:00">May 6, 2008 <span class="timestamp">4:01 pm</span>
<span class="comment-link"><a href="#comment-59227" title="Comment Permalink">Link</a></span> </span>
</div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>We must be on the same wavelength today. First you blogged about clarified butter &#8230; which reminded me that it is just great for making popcorn &#8212; so I just had to go make some. Now I&#8217;ve finished munching, I&#8217;m back and what do I see &#8230;<br />
Skip the bag. A big pot does just fine. Heat up the clarified butter high, add kernels, close lid, let pop. Don&#8217;t shake the pot. Easy.<br />
Who knows what the paper bag is really made of.</p>
<cite>&#8212; Maria</cite>
</div>
