<li class="alt" id="comment-59197">
<div class="comment-meta">
<span class="comment-number">11. </span>
<span class="updated" title="2008-05-06T14:49:58+00:00">May 6, 2008 <span class="timestamp">4:36 pm</span>
<span class="comment-link"><a href="#comment-59197" title="Comment Permalink">Link</a></span> </span>
</div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>Diacetyl &#8211; the artificial butter flavor in most microwave popcorn &#8211; is not very dangerous in normal quantities. Where it&#8217;s been a health hazard is at the plants where microwave popcorn is manufactured; there have been several cases of debilitating &#8220;popcorn lung&#8221; at them. There&#8217;s only one known occurrence of this in a popcorn consumer, by someone who made and ate two bags a day for a decade, and it was much more mild.</p>
<p>(I don&#8217;t want to defend prepackaged microwave popcorn and/or artificial butter-flavored grease, but it does nobody any help to overstate the problem. For what it&#8217;s worth, diacetyl occurs naturally in beer fermentation; whether it&#8217;s considered a nice flavor note or a flaw depends on the style.)</p>
<cite>&#8212; Nathan Williams</cite>
</div>
</li>
<li id="comment-59199">
<div class="comment-meta">
<span class="comment-number">12. </span>
<span class="updated" title="2008-05-06T14:49:58+00:00">May 6, 2008 <span class="timestamp">4:39 pm</span>
<span class="comment-link"><a href="#comment-59199" title="Comment Permalink">Link</a></span> </span>
</div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>Years ago we went to a demonstration farm here in the Bay Area, Ardenwood, where everything is 19th century. (No boomboxes or frisbees allowed on the property &#8211; bring your bike &amp; picnic stuff but no motorized toys). The organic farm always has some demo on the weekend &#8211; walnut hulling, wool carding, ice cream making, etc. One time they were showing us popcorn &#8211; hulling it on the cob, popping it on the outdoor woodstove, feeding us the results. Then they gave the kids popcorn cobs &#8211; kernels on the cob! &#8211; as take-home presents. They told us to put a cob in a paper bag and microwave it. End of story. </p>
<p>I thought that was so cool&#8230; but it didn&#8217;t occur to me that any old loose popcorn could also pop in a bag. Way to go, Mark!</p>
<cite>&#8212; Leila Abu-Saba</cite>
</div>
