<li class="alt" id="comment-59185">
<div class="comment-meta">
<span class="comment-number">21. </span>
<span class="updated" title="2008-05-06T14:49:58+00:00">May 7, 2008 <span class="timestamp">4:51 am</span>
<span class="comment-link"><a href="#comment-59185" title="Comment Permalink">Link</a></span> </span>
</div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>I&#8217;ve used this method for a couple years with success. I find it preferable to the stove top becuase it doesn&#8217;t dirty a pot and you can do it without adding fat. I generally use staples, but if you don&#8217;t want the fire hazard you can fold the bag shut once or twice and make a few small tears in the folded portion. It holds together quite well, thereby mitigating the likelihood of the bag opening and filling the base of your microwave with popcorn, which has happened to me a couple times when going simply with folding.</p>
<cite>&#8212; Drew</cite>
</div>
</li>
<li id="comment-59231">
<div class="comment-meta">
<span class="comment-number">22. </span>
<span class="updated" title="2008-05-06T14:49:58+00:00">May 7, 2008 <span class="timestamp">8:26 am</span>
<span class="comment-link"><a href="#comment-59231" title="Comment Permalink">Link</a></span> </span>
</div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>The &#8220;old-fashioned&#8221; (dating back to the 70s?) air popper is also great and easy, if you don&#8217;t like this paper bag idea. It takes no longer than microwave popcorn, and requires no butter or oil as with stovetop version (if you&#8217;d rather have a lower calorie snack).</p>
<cite>&#8212; melon</cite>
</div>
</li>
<li class="alt" id="comment-59233">
<div class="comment-meta">
<span class="comment-number">23. </span>
<span class="updated" title="2008-05-06T14:49:58+00:00">May 7, 2008 <span class="timestamp">8:49 am</span>
