<div class="comment-content">
<p>After discovering that one of the ingredients in a bag of &#8220;corn on the cob&#8221; flavored microwave popcorn was fish oil, I am giving up any temptation to purchase these products. Very often, I do the stovetop thing, anyway, and melt the butter in the microwave.</p>
<cite>&#8212; Kristi</cite>
</div>
</li>
<li class="alt" id="comment-59237">
<div class="comment-meta">
<span class="comment-number">25. </span>
<span class="updated" title="2008-05-06T14:49:58+00:00">May 7, 2008 <span class="timestamp">9:47 am</span>
<span class="comment-link"><a href="#comment-59237" title="Comment Permalink">Link</a></span> </span>
</div>
<div class="comment-content">
<p>I&#8217;m still an adherent of good air-popped popcorn.  Why bother with all the trouble (and waste) when you can just throw a cup of kernels in and get a great big bowl in a few minutes?  Granted, I&#8217;m not a butter or oil lover &#8211; I prefer a nice handful of fresh grated parmigiana with some dried minced onion, and maybe some Old Bay.  A good air popper only costs about $15, maybe $20.  (Any more than than, and you&#8217;re being ripped off!)  And they last forever.  I just replaced my Presto Poplite &#8211; my first one was from the 80&#8217;s, found at a flea market find, and it lasted 6 years!</p>
<cite>&#8212; Eris</cite>
</div>
